====>    JAVA : 
•	High-level
•	Object-oriented
•	Platform independent
•	Principle- write once, run anywhere
•	Code runs on JVM instead of the operating system
-Code
public class Hello
{
	public static void main(String[] args)
	{
		System.out.println("Hello Java");
	}
}

====>    JVM (Java Virtual Machine):
•	Runtime engine
•	 Convert bytecode -> machine-readable code
•	 Handling Garbage collection, memory managemnet(Heap,stack),JIT compilation, platform independence.
NOTE- 
Heap → Objects, Selenium WebElement instances
Stack → Method calls, local variables
Method Area → Class metadata
PC Register → Tracks instructions
Native Method Area → Native code
Real-time:
When Selenium loads large pages, objects are stored in Heap; garbage collector cleans unused ones.

====>    JDK (Java Development Kit):
•	Containing JRE + Complier(javac) + tools(jarsigner,jdb)
•	 Writing, compiling, and debugging 

====>    JRE (Java Runtime Environment):
•	 Provides libraries and a JVM required to run a Java application

====>    Data Types:
•	Primitive: byte, short, int, long, float, double, char, Boolean
•	 Non-Primitive: String, arrays, classes, interfaces
-code: 
int age = 25;
double salary = 55000.75;
char grade = 'A';
boolean isActive = true;

====>    Variables:
•	Store data in memory
•	Type: Local, Instance(non-static), Static(class variables)
-Code:
	public class Name
	{
		static String company = "ABC";  // Static variable
		int id = 101; 					// instance variable
		
		public void display()
		{
			String str = "XYZ";			//Local variable
			System.out.println(str);
		}
	}

====>    Operators:
•	Perform operations on variables and values.
•	Types: Arithmetic, Relational, Logical, Assignment, Unary, Ternary.
-Code:
	int a=10, b=20;
	System.out.println(a+b);  // Arithmetic
	System.out.println(a>b);  // Realtional
	System.out.println(a!=b); // Logical

====>    Input / Output:
•	Input: Scanner
•	Output: System.out.println()-
-Code:
		import java.util.Scanner;
		public class IOExample {
		public static void main(String[] args) {
			Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
			System.out.print("Enter name: ");
			String name = sc.nextLine();
			System.out.println("Hello " + name);
			}
		}


====>  	  Conditional Statement:
•	Types: if, if-else, else-if, switch
-Code:
		int marks = 75;
		if (marks >= 90) {
		System.out.println("Excellent");
		} else if (marks >= 60) {
		System.out.println("Good");
		} else {
		System.out.println("Needs Improvement");
		}

====>    Loops:
•	Types: for, while, do-while
-Code:
		for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
		System.out.println("Count: " + i);
		}









